but they are extremely
restricted since the 1980s.

01:20:29.690 --> 01:20:33.500
So there is also the
outsider distortion of history

01:20:33.500 --> 01:20:38.580
of the Assyrians, there is a far
greater focus on church divisions

01:20:38.580 --> 01:20:40.450
in the Assyrian community,

01:20:40.450 --> 01:20:47.080 position:56%
various patriarchates then there
are the factors that unite Assyrians

01:20:47.080 --> 01:20:51.670
which is their language and
their historical narrative.

01:20:51.670 --> 01:20:57.510
The rise of nationalism as Alda
has said or was it you Fadi?

01:20:57.510 --> 01:21:02.790
Nationalisms in the Middle East and
the post-World War II period meant

01:21:02.790 --> 01:21:06.260 position:56%
that there is non-recognition of the
Assyrian ethnicity and I think Alda

01:21:06.260 --> 01:21:10.610
and Fadi have both spoken to
this very well, only recognition

01:21:10.610 --> 01:21:12.270
of the church institutions.

01:21:12.270 --> 01:21:17.730
Now, I say except Iran I don't mean
that Iran is exceptionally good

01:21:17.730 --> 01:21:21.560
in this regard, but there is
some difference between how Iran

01:21:21.560 --> 01:21:25.620
and the rest of the Middle
East regard the Assyrians

01:21:25.620 --> 01:21:26.950
in terms of ethnicity.

01:21:26.950 --> 01:21:30.110
The churches are not active

01:21:30.110 --> 01:21:34.640
in promoting the living
language but mainly Syriac.

01:21:34.640 --> 01:21:39.310
Syriac is an Aramaic language and
sometimes it wasn't very clear

01:21:39.310 --> 01:21:42.280
in this conference, it is an
Aramaic language developed

01:21:42.280 --> 01:21:46.160
in Ohai [assumed spelling] but
it is now a liturgical language,

01:21:46.160 --> 01:21:48.150
it's not a spoken language.

01:21:48.150 --> 01:21:52.390
It is the language of the chants
and all of the Assyrian Churches.

01:21:52.390 --> 01:21:57.240
Imagine a whole Czechoslovanak
continue to be taught

01:21:57.240 --> 01:22:01.010
in this Slovak language areas
rather than the living language.

01:22:01.010 --> 01:22:04.620
So the living language in fact
is suffering at the expense

01:22:04.620 --> 01:22:07.240
of the teaching of
Syriac in the Churches.

01:22:07.240 --> 01:22:12.910
The Baathist regime in Syria also
forced closed Assyrians schools

01:22:12.910 --> 01:22:18.010
which had been doing relatively
well in places like Qamishli.

01:22:18.010 --> 01:22:21.110
Iraq had functioning schools
and [inaudible] playing

01:22:21.110 --> 01:22:24.460
and mainly supported by the
diaspora using the books

01:22:24.460 --> 01:22:30.160
of Kurish Fanyaaman [assumed
spelling] who is a relative of one

01:22:30.160 --> 01:22:35.490
of our panelists, yes,
and reprinted from Iran.

01:22:35.490 --> 01:22:42.750
The Syrian Orthodox Church actively
discouraged the literary production

01:22:42.750 --> 01:22:46.170
of [foreign language] because,
which is the Western language

01:22:46.170 --> 01:22:49.310
that is used in the community.

01:22:49.310 --> 01:22:53.650
The spoken and written
language today are largely based

01:22:53.650 --> 01:22:56.660
on the works of Iranian Assyrians.

01:22:56.660 --> 01:23:00.820
Now, I don't say that only because
I come from the Ormy region,

01:23:00.820 --> 01:23:04.630
I say it because the
education of Assyrians in Iran

01:23:04.630 --> 01:23:10.380
and their vernacular language was
far stronger and less restricted

01:23:10.380 --> 01:23:13.870
in the last fifty years than
anywhere else in the Middle East.

01:23:13.870 --> 01:23:21.230
So there is a great reliance on
the works of Assyrians from Iran

01:23:21.230 --> 01:23:26.830 position:56%
for the poetry that exists today,
for the plays and for the histories,

01:23:26.830 --> 01:23:29.060
the anthologies and so forth.

01:23:29.060 --> 01:23:32.500
Even though Ormy was
not the first place

01:23:32.500 --> 01:23:37.500
where the language must vernacular
was committed to writing,

01:23:37.500 --> 01:23:39.160
it was in fact in Alqosh
[assumed spelling]

01:23:39.160 --> 01:23:44.480
about which my colleagues
have spoken.

01:23:44.480 --> 01:23:50.850
Schools, however, In Iran
have had a rocky history.

01:23:50.850 --> 01:23:54.770
The Friday language schools,
Friday being the Muslim holiday

01:23:54.770 --> 01:24:02.070
with when we studied primary
level vernacular in Church schools

01:24:02.070 --> 01:24:05.250
and also in secular schools such
as in Hamagan [assumed spelling]

01:24:05.250 --> 01:24:12.080
in the 1930s and Abadan [assumed
spelling] in the 1950s and 60s

01:24:12.080 --> 01:24:15.760
in Olmin [assumed spelling]
and most importantly in Tehran.

01:24:15.760 --> 01:24:18.140
And I think we have
several people in this room

01:24:18.140 --> 01:24:24.320
who are actually graduates from the
very important school in Tehran.

01:24:24.320 --> 01:24:30.060
In the 1960s, the work of
the [foreign language] Tehran

01:24:30.060 --> 01:24:32.820
which is the youth
organization of Assyrians

01:24:32.820 --> 01:24:36.340
of Tehran became extremely
significant in the promotion

01:24:36.340 --> 01:24:43.410
of literature and history and
poetry as well as performing arts.

01:24:43.410 --> 01:24:49.180
Catholic schools have continued
to teach languages in some areas

01:24:49.180 --> 01:24:53.140
that I have spoken about but the
Protestant schools which had been

01:24:53.140 --> 01:24:59.210
so strong in the late 19th and
pre-Diaspora period have collapsed

01:24:59.210 --> 01:25:02.660
because in 1961 the Protestant
Churches simply pulled

01:25:02.660 --> 01:25:07.880
out of that sort of thing.

01:25:07.880 --> 01:25:12.280
From words to music means
that the tension of Assyrians,

01:25:12.280 --> 01:25:18.660
the ability to support a wide range
of culture was extremely limited.

01:25:18.660 --> 01:25:24.520
So for a long period of time, the
people who retained the language,

01:25:24.520 --> 01:25:28.040
the poetry, the music
were popular singers.

01:25:28.040 --> 01:25:30.050
And here I'm calling them
weddings singers just

01:25:30.050 --> 01:25:34.510
because it's a popular term that is
used in Greek and Jewish culture,

01:25:34.510 --> 01:25:38.820
but in fact these are people who
would perform at entertainments,

01:25:38.820 --> 01:25:41.700
they would New Year's
celebrations and so forth.

01:25:41.700 --> 01:25:50.730
And they would sing songs that
related to patriotism rather

01:25:50.730 --> 01:25:55.110
than simply I love you, you are
my love, and so forth and so on.

01:25:55.110 --> 01:26:00.190
There was that too but interspersed
in all of these was a great deal

01:26:00.190 --> 01:26:02.830
of patriotic poetry
and patriotic music.

01:26:02.830 --> 01:26:06.510
Some of it written by the
performance themselves.

01:26:06.510 --> 01:26:08.030
This particular gentleman born

01:26:08.030 --> 01:26:14.790
in Baghdad 1949 [inaudible]
is probably the best known

01:26:14.790 --> 01:26:19.840 position:56%
and the best loved of the persons
in this category of Assyrian singers

01:26:19.840 --> 01:26:23.050
who are still revered I would say

01:26:23.050 --> 01:26:26.200
because of the role they had
played in retaining patriotism.

01:26:26.200 --> 01:26:32.300
Art songs, compositions from the
19th century are mainly lost,

01:26:32.300 --> 01:26:34.190
mainly due to the Diaspora
and the fact

01:26:34.190 --> 01:26:38.430
that preservation methods were
simply not there as we have them

01:26:38.430 --> 01:26:41.010
in the post-World War I period.

01:26:41.010 --> 01:26:47.360
Some of the early 78 RPMs recorded
are often from the Diaspora dealing

01:26:47.360 --> 01:26:52.060
with themes of nationalism
in some instances

01:26:52.060 --> 01:26:56.140
in some [inaudible] history and
some instances playing love songs

01:26:56.140 --> 01:27:00.060
but all in the Aramaic language.

01:27:00.060 --> 01:27:04.920
Poetry, theater and the performing
arts preservation have been

01:27:04.920 --> 01:27:09.690
difficult as I have been saying
but we do have some anthologies

01:27:09.690 --> 01:27:14.760
of poetry from the late 19th
and 20th century, not much.

01:27:14.760 --> 01:27:18.410
But these have been preserved in a
book by Samath [assumed spelling]

01:27:18.410 --> 01:27:23.840
to which the fundamental book on
Assyrian literature and poetry,

01:27:23.840 --> 01:27:32.140
the book by Rudolph Matsu 1975 I
think is based in large respect.

01:27:32.140 --> 01:27:37.080
Before World War I the Assyrians
in Iran had four periodicals,

01:27:37.080 --> 01:27:41.090
the earliest being in 1849 which is
the earliest periodical published

01:27:41.090 --> 01:27:43.090
anywhere in Iran.

01:27:43.090 --> 01:27:48.280 position:56%
And in Ottoman Turkey there were two
and Fadi referred to one of them,

01:27:48.280 --> 01:27:53.340
I think, Georgia there was
one because of this migration

01:27:53.340 --> 01:27:58.230
from Ormy especially to
Russia, Tsarist Russia.

01:27:58.230 --> 01:28:03.230
And then that's about
it before World War I.

01:28:03.230 --> 01:28:08.620
After World War I in the Middle
East in Diaspora there were many,

01:28:08.620 --> 01:28:13.280
many Assyrian publications
in the United States -

01:28:13.280 --> 01:28:15.930
short-lived not institutionally
supported.

01:28:15.930 --> 01:28:20.260
And I was hoping and I know that
the Library of Congress has a lot

01:28:20.260 --> 01:28:22.940
of these periodicals, but they are
very precious and so they're not

01:28:22.940 --> 01:28:26.270
in that room for display but
really they are wonderful

01:28:26.270 --> 01:28:29.100
and a wonderful collection
exists here.

01:28:29.100 --> 01:28:32.960
There are also church
publications, so these tend to be

01:28:32.960 --> 01:28:36.450
in the native language
but in Diaspora they have

01:28:36.450 --> 01:28:38.630
to adopt other languages as well.

01:28:38.630 --> 01:28:42.020
So they are often bilingual
sometimes trilingual

01:28:42.020 --> 01:28:44.300
because of the immigration
especially with Arabic,

01:28:44.300 --> 01:28:49.720
and in the Middle East itself
too they are tending to be more

01:28:49.720 --> 01:28:54.160
and more trilingual and bilingual,
in part because there are fewer

01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:56.250
and fewer people who'd
actually can write

01:28:56.250 --> 01:28:59.340
in these languages in
the Aramaic language.

01:28:59.340 --> 01:29:04.700
And also because of the fact
that their readership requires it

01:29:04.700 --> 01:29:11.870
and there is State censorship
that requires national languages.

01:29:11.870 --> 01:29:14.440
Now, the rights of the theatrical

01:29:14.440 --> 01:29:17.340
and performing arts is an
